textDisplay:
Hey, so before I talk about anything else I want to say that I was interviewed on my friend Coca’s podcast, if you’d like a little insight into my creative process and shit I think you’ll really enjoy it: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DR8V2fLps6U

I’ve also started selling merch, for anyone who wanted to support my channel financially without using my Patreon. Hiring artists to do the designs for me since I want them to actually be decent looking, gonna make a video once I’ve got a couple more: https://www.designbyhumans.com/shop/ShammyTV/

OKAY now that that’s out of the way, I should explain what made this video take so long, aside from the obvious fact that it’s roughly 4 times as long as the reviews I used to make when I was posting monthly:

TL;DR - While working on this review I was dealing with some personal mental health problems, partially brought on by stress and partially brought on by the fact that I had to put down two childhood dogs during the writing process. Throw in the fact that I was talking about a game that I’m really not passionate about at this point and you get a recipe for a 4 month creation timeline, and that’s not even mentioning my steadily rising stupid level of detail that I put into these reviews in both the editing and writing process, as far as I can remember there are more hidden jokes in this review than normal ones.

Which leads me to another point - I’m not going to be making any more long form reviews like this one in the near future, and if I ever make one again it’s going to be for a game I *really* care about so that i don’t run out of steam halfway through working on it. I know these reviews are a bit contentious with my audience, I’ve heard an equal number of people saying they prefer either the shorter and longer reviews, but for my own sake I’m going to be moving back to around 15-20 minute videos. My goal for this year is to upload at least 1 high quality video per month, and I’m very excited about the three I’ve got lined up after this one.

Sorry this took me so long to make, I’ve been staring at it for so long I don’t even know if it’s bearable to watch. Hope you liked it.

Also, for anyone who isn’t aware, I do a bi-weekly podcast with 3 of my friends called “Please Stop Talking.” The first episode was pretty rough but I think we’ve really found our footing, and if you like my reviews I think there’s a good chance you’ll enjoy it. Here’s a recent episode about the Game Awards: https://soundcloud.com/pstpodcast/please-stop-talking-12-the-game-awards-2017

Thank you to CREO for letting me use their song Afterglow in this review, you should check them out: https://soundcloud.com/creotheband

Now for other links:

Twitter: https://twitter.com/ShammyTV
Patreon: https://patreon.com/shammy
Twitch: https://twitch.tv/shammyyt
Second Channel: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC1LpNC2yPRYaXhEH8H8n1FA

textDisplay:
I really like your humor. It fits the character your going with and is not overly melancholic or sassy. The highs and lows of this character are noticeable, but not annoyingly overstated (And, of course, the highs are scarce compared to the lows). The owl is also a charming carrier of that personality. With the constant "I'm annoyed" expression the character is perfectly described, without having had to actually state it. I'm new to the channel, so I'm not sure if there actually may be some kind of character development. Also, the american badass tropes are not overdone and flow into the gag without being too annoying (which I like a lot, since it retains your pride for your country, but doesn't take over the figurative stage)
Though, I find your alcoholism and self-loathing gags to be melodramatic and unfitting for the "I don't want to be here" and "I'm right" kind of character you made. Maybe I'm talking out of my ass and you deliberately crafted this character to be this way, as to make it seem desperate to be liked, though it already has kind of given up on that. However, I remain with what I said: It's unfitting. More fitting would be a fokus on the "I'm right/ better" part of the character and making it a character that feels itself to be better than others, with the desperation being retained by the occasional "God, I feel like shit" moment. I think that would give you more space for jokes as well as it would pronounce those that are actually kind of funny. Indeed, your approach to the "fanbase pressure" gag was not only unoriginal, but also unfunny. For a creator that really got me interested in what he was trying to say and being funny troughout stepwise, I believe that you can definitely do better than that.
I would like to add that I'm in no way an actual critic and just tried to get across how I feel about your alter ego.

TL;DR: Luv ya. Got sub. Got liek.

textDisplay:
The reason why starting galaxy is called Euclid Galaxy is probably because it's a reference to a mathematical definition of *Euclid space* -- which is basically just a simple kind of linear multidimensional space. The space we live in, if we don't count time, is a 3-dimensional Euclid space, and if you had an infinite sheet of paper, it would be a 2-dimensional Euclid space. The name of the second galaxy also hints at it -- it's called Hilbert Dimension, which is a reference to Hilbert space -- another kind of space with different properties.

Believe it or not, there are more galaxies after that, and they lose consistency in naming after the second one -- the third one is called Callypso Galaxy.

The part around 38 minutes in, I kinda want it to instead be "wanting to do business with Sony Interactive Entertainment, after the clusterfuck of them massively overhyping an indie game". Because yes, the game has flaws and had a lot more flaws...but I also feel like many of that was exacerbated by the gulf in expectations. And as you say, Hello games does seem to be trying very hard to fix the stuff, to improve their game...and it will never succeed, because it's trying to rebuild and reach a towering mountain that it has long since passed.

The context is all important, and if we were experiencing this game out on steam as early access, then eventually being released on Ps4, probably with a "early access, experience may change" sticker, like on PuBg? I think peoples perception would be vastly different, they'd still see the same flaws...but they'd be hopeful for the future, not embittered by the past.

textDisplay:
"I'm not at all against games or works of art striving to have a deeper meaning beneath the surface, but if Jackson Pollock had paint rollers for hands, he wouldn't use strokes this fucking broad."

That is a profoundly admirable statement! I have no respect for creators who leave their works open to interpretation by ambiguous half-references. Art is an interpretation of an aspect of reality as seen through the artist's lens. It is meant to convey something specific about reality which the artist deems important and essential. This is the only proper premise of art. It is the foundation of the purest form of creative expression: romanticism.

Creating art with definite form is not easy. The creator must distill a specific, clear message from the medium. Thus, it follows that the unfocused creator of No Man's Sky would sloppily integrate a convoluted mess of philosophic influences after release merely to satisfy justifiably angry consumers. A story cannot be tacked on to an established, complex work like No Man's Sky without contradictions and deepities.

Kickass review, Shammy. Very thoughtful.

textDisplay:
16:30 *RAISES* the question, not begs.  Surely a wise owl such as Shammy is aware that this is like the most commonly misused phrase in the English language.  Shammy clearly misspoke or was using the phrase ironically.    

For those who aren't aware: "Begging the Question" is another name for the fallacy of Circular Reasoning.  For example, "I know the Bible is true because the Bible says so!"  

Basically every time you've heard someone say "begs the question," they should have just said "raises the question."  But this one is misused often enough that the real meaning is buried.

textDisplay:
16 is an important number in computer science.

using base 16, you can represent every possible computer byte (of which there are 256, which is 16^2) with two digits, from 00 to FF. 

16 to the power of 16 (18,446,744,073,709,551,616 - the number of planets in No Man's Sky) is the maximum value of a 'long integer' - a hardware limitation turned into a story hook by setting the game in a computer simulation.

this is the Occam's razor answer, for the record.

Also, subscribed.

textDisplay:
Okay (sigh). Even if I never play this trash-heap of a game. Even if I never learn another thing about it. Even if I lost all faith in it once I started seeing actual game-play, despite adoring the initial teaser trailer like so many other people. Ret-conning the game so that it's universe is nothing more than a simulation inside an in-game computer system is the stupidest, dumbest, most insulting update they could have possibly made. 

I don't want Skyrim to be a story some old man is telling his grandchildren about the fire-place. I want it to be a real place in the game that I am actually adventuring through and affecting for better or worse. I don't want Half-Life 2 to be the mental delusions of a man who went into a coma after the accident where the portal generator exploded in the first game. I want it to be a real in-game universe so that my actions will lead to the destruction of the invading alien forces, and so that my relationship with Alyx can have a meaningful weight to it.

I get that the story was also added really late to NMS, but nullifying the entire world as a part of that story is complete BS.

textDisplay:
Actually, Genesis 16 fits very well, but I don't think it was connection intended.
The entire point of this story, is failing to fulfill a promise. God made a promise to Abraham: "Look toward heaven, and number the stars, if you are able to number them. So shall your descendants be.” But Abraham's wife was past child-bearing age, so he tried to fulfill this promise, by producing offspring from his slave.
However, it didn't fulfill the promise. Ishmael wasn't the "descendant" God envisioned. The promise could only be fulfilled by a miracle from God: woman that should be infertile, bore a son.

Similarly, Hello Games made a promise: "Look to the number 6 trillion, if you are able. So shall the content in our game be." But they were only a small studio, so they tried to fulfill this promise by procedural generation.
However, it didn't fulfill the promise. Infinite number of crappy planets weren't the "content" people hyped for the game envisioned. The promise could only be fulfilled by a miracle. 
But here, parallelism ends. Because unlike the biblical story of Abraham and his descendants, miracle didn't happen.

textDisplay:
You know what would have made this game better?  I have a few things.

1. An EXP system with various skills sort of like a Runescape type of thing.  You have mining skill, flying skill, running skill, trading skill, strength skill, armor skill, etc...whatever else you can think of.  This would encourage you to enjoy doing even the mst monotonous things, since you'd always be getting EXP, even just running.

2.  The ability to wear actual armor.  Maybe they protect from different types of weather, increase your health or defense, or have certain perks that can help you in the game.

3.  The ability to kill creatures on other planets and collect drops from them and gain EXP.  Find a powerful creature?  You may get a rare drop.

4.  A procedurally generated boss on every single planet. Super powerful, all unique looking with different attacks.

5. The ability to create bases without having to fly to the stupid ass space station to pick up a crew member.  God, I hated this.  Honestly, if the game just let you be able to do everything on one planet, I'd be set.  I like my base planet, I hate having to fly everywhere unless I want to see a new planet that I haven't been to yet.  This brings me to my final and probably biggest point.

6. Take the manual flying out completely.  I know they were trying to go for a realistic thing here, but my God...those flying segments are absolute garbage.  I don't want to wait 4 minutes to get to another planet, pick up a certain item or somethin, then hav to go back.  The lack of convenience that comes from going from planet to planet is just horrible.  This is the biggest thing that makes me not enjoy this game.  They still could keep everything else in the game about ship mantence and whatnot, but if I have the ability to fly to a planet that is close by, just let me select it and be done with it.

textDisplay: You should review No Man's Sky again

I played this off a friend of mine's steam account a while after it first came out. It took me about 8 hours of fucking around to finally realize I could sit around in the game's local trading station and just buy X item from one of the very limited cast of trading vendor archtypes the game devs had set in place and sell it another of the very limited traders for about four times the profit. Consistently. Within an hour I had gone from a modest 28 slot ship I had bought before to a 40+ capacity 3,000,000 credit ship I had straight up bought from one of the other traders. It was at that point I quit. It was the last straw of laziness on the developers part I could take. 

It's a very good looking game, the initial veneer meant to lure people in. Unfortunately it's also a very empty vapid game. One that takes a while to notice with how "grand" a charade of a front the game puts up before the illusion starts to chip away when you start looking more closely under the hood and notice the trends. 

So it's kind of a fitting slap in the face that they decided to use the same lazy no effort approach to end with the it's all just a simulation trope.

textDisplay:
Or... 16 is referenced because of the 16*16 references. 16*16 is 256. 256 is the number of values held in a byte. If the world is beating you overhead with the idea of being a simulation, literally referencing a byte (in terms of both displaying a number and have the way it's dispalyed feel incredibly artificial) is a fine way to do that... If you're Hello Games.

Why 16? It's the square root of 256, as well as a power of two. Every digit in binary deals with a power of 2.

16 itself is also not without value in a computing world, as Hexadecimal was a number display system devised to be able to write exactly 256 values in 2 digits of numbers. Whereas 10 is well... 10, in our current way of writing numbers, 10 actually represents 16 in hexadecimal. Hence, the core of writing 256 values in a sane manner isn't finding 256 unique characters to assign values to, it's using 16 different characters to represent 16 different values, and splitting that up over 2 digits.

I'd be willing to believe that if you just shotgun 16, piles of fourth wall breaking 16's, 16*16, and its product, 256, you could make anyone who knows much about binary or even some scripting languages or game modding/design FEEL smart for making the connection without being told so, but without actually requiring them to be smart.

Since this is Hello Games we're talking about... I'd argue it's not beyond consideration.

textDisplay:
I think most of the people who shunned no man's sky in the first place didn't actually want a space exploration simulator. They wanted a combination of halo and freespace.

I pre-ordered the game, and what I was expecting was a game where you fly about in space and explore stuff. That's what I got. It had too much mining for me initially, and too many life support systems to keep recharging, but when creative mode came out, those complaints got addressed.

Now I have two creative mode saves, one of them I started while watching this video. I think if someone's an average hardcore gamer, whether they're the COD kind or the witcher kind or the 4x strategy game kind, they probably won't get much out of this game, but if you like the concept of exploring space with some pretty scenery, and I do, then this game has plenty of that.

I think your review is pretty good, although I haven't played through much of the story yet because I like just hanging out. We're not going to get close to magic sci-fi spaceships before I die, so this game gets me pretty close. At least, it gets me pretty close without having to have an internet connection or having to log in to a multiplayer service. Isn't that a novel idea, elite dangerous?

textDisplay:
Can I be FUCKING real for a second?

This community is fucking atrocious right now. You're all acting like a bunch of whiny, entitled little babies.

A tiny team of people made an entire universe for you to explore. They made it for YOU, and they're going to wake up tomorrow morning and see that instead of enjoying it, this community of "fans" picked out the 3 or 4 things that weren't perfect and are using that to fucking riot.

Guess what? The game was never going to be perfect. It was never going to live up to your hype. It was never going to be everything you'd ever want in a game.

What it WAS going to be was an impossibly big universe filled with mysteries and weird shit. I just played it for 2 hours and it was exactly that. What more do you want?

Is it buggy? Sure. Is it repetitive? Maybe. Is the inventory system imperfect and the multiplayer feature questionable and the structure unclear? Sure, fine.

But holy shit what do these people OWE YOU?

How fucking entitled do you have to be to explore an infinite universe in a spaceship and then say "yeah but..."

We should all be fucking weeping in our chairs right now at the sheer size and scale of the achievement. We should be showering the people behind this thing with the praise they deserve for pulling off one of the most inspiring games in recent memory.

Hello Games doesn't owe you the world. Yet they gave you 18 QUINTILLION of them.

If you have the fucking audacity to complain about it then you don't deserve it and you were never fans in the first place.
